(131,	50,	'I have placed several calls to DOJ (No response).  Sent the following email on 11/13/2012.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nFrom: Kerry Lewis\r\nSent: Tuesday, November 13, 2012 1:20 PM\r\nTo: Sybil.barksdale@usdoj.gov\r\nSubject: Referral Ms. Valerie Yancey - Domestic Violence Case Management\r\n\r\n\r\nHello Ms. Barksdale,\r\n\r\nBy way of introduction, my name is Kerry Lewis, President of Atechra, Inc.  Ms. Valerie Yancey thought it would beneficial to contact you regarding the case management system we developed exclusively for domestic violence related cases.\r\n\r\nThe reason for the calls I have place to you is my company specializes in a software system made specifically to meet the needs of domestic violence case management and shelters.  On several occasions Executive Directors of intake centers and or  shelters have strongly suggest that we reach out to agencies such as yours, in efforts to get the Domestic Violence Intake (DVI) package incorporated as a part of their grant award.  \r\n\r\nWhy DVI? It streamlines the process of aiding victims of domestic abuse.  As I am sure you know, the intake procedure used by most intake centers, shelters and agencies involves a redundant series of questions. Over and over, domestic violence victims answer the same questions about the incident, their personal information, and their needs. This inefficiency takes a DOUBLE TOLL – TRAUMATIZED PEOPLE ARE FORCED TO WADE THROUGH A FLOOD OF PAPERWORK, RELIVING THE ABUSE EACH TIME THEY RECOUNT IT FOR ANOTHER FACILITY. Our software hastens the intake process, and allows victims to more speedily get the assistance they need.  Intake personnel can get all the information they need ONCE – and collaborate with related agencies at the touch of a button.  In one step, violence case identification, management, law and social services, sheltering, and child protection needs are determined.  \r\n\r\nAttached you will find a brief document that provides an introduction to the DVI case management system.  In addition, I would also like the opportunity to discuss how DVI could possibly assist the OWA in its mission “to provide federal leadership in developing the nation’s capacity to reduce violence against women and administer justice for and strengthen services to victims of domestic violence, dating violence, sexual assault, and stalking.”\r\n\r\nI look forward to speaking with you soon.\r\n\r\n',	'DVI Introduction.pdf',	'1352911380.pdf',	2,	'2012-11-14 11:43:00'),
